  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Contemporary work on the nature of truth appears to have arisen in response to Hegel’s views that dominated the philosophical communities of the United States and Britain during the nineteenth century.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Hegelianism appears to have waned after a fondness for scientific conclusions emerged, which was piqued by the promise of the natural and physical sciences.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Nowhere else was this naturalisation of truth more apparent than in an editorial published in an 1873 issue of the Scientific American.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "The editorial, “Knowledge of the Truth,” was not an explicit indictment of idealism but it compelled readers to shed “imaginary cosmologies” for a return to the “greatest boon which man can ever possibly obtain: The Knowledge of the Truth” through observations of a mind-independent world.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "The end of Hegelianism and the rise of contemporary discussions on truth was the result of the confluence of three sources: two infamous and a third all but overlooked.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "First, the infamous death knell against Hegelianism was sounded by G.E. Moore and Bertrand Russell in 1902 and 1903, respectively.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Both favoured a correspondence theory of truth, and both found Hegelianism metaphysically and epistemologically repugnant.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The second source of contemporary discussion on truth was the pragmatists, especially William James, John Dewey, and Charles Sanders Peirce.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "None of the theories on offer by any one of them necessarily has overlapping similarities with any of the other in the triumverate.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Third and finally, the overlooked but highly influential reason for the demise of Hegelianism and the rise of contemporary work on truth may be traced to the rise of realism.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "In the United States, the “American Six” published a manifesto in 1910 that established the doctrinal priorities for philosophical thought in the twentieth century—including the investigation of “relational” accounts of truth.",
      "label": "premise"
    }
  },
